{"title_page": "Jabal Haraz", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name              = Jabal Haraz\n| native_name       = {{lang|ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632}}\n| native_name_lang  = ar\n| photo             = Yemen (11462772954).jpg\n| photo_caption     = A building with terraces overlooks the side of one of the Haraz mountains\n| country           = {{YEM}}\n| region_type       = \n| region            = Asia\n| border            =\n| highest           = \n| elevation_m       = 3,000\n| highest_location  = \n| coordinates       = {{coord|15.1667|N|43.7500|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n| range_coordinates =\n| length_km         = \n| geology           =\n| period            =\n| orogeny           =\n| map               = Yemen#Middle East#Asia\n| map_image         = \n| map_caption       = \n}}\n\n'''Jabal Haraz''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632|Jabal \u1e24ar\u0101z}}) is a mountain region of [[Yemen]], between [[Sana'a]] and [[Al Hudaydah|Al-Hudaydah]]. In the 11th century, it was the stronghold of the [[Sulaihid State|Sulaihid]] dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive today.<ref name=unesco>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1722/ |title=Jabal Haraz |publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |date=2002-07-08 |access-date=2009-03-24}}</ref> They include [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]], the highest mountain in Yemen and the [[Arabian Peninsula]],<ref name=\"Laughlin2008\">{{cite book |last=McLaughlin |first=Daniel |title=Yemen |publisher=[[Bradt Travel Guides]] |chapter=1: Background |page=3 |isbn=978-1-8416-2212-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQvhZaEVzjcC&pg |year=2008}}</ref> and are considered part of the [[Sarawat Mountains|Sarat range]].<ref name=\"CookFarmer2013\">{{cite book |last1=Cook |first1=John |last2=Farmer |first2=G. Thomas |title=Climate Change Science: A Modern Synthesis |volume=1 \u2013 The Physical Climate |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer Science & Business Media]] |chapter=VI: Land and Its Climates |page=334 |isbn=9-4007-5757-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tbtEAAAAQBAJ&dq=sarawat+mountains&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2013-01-12}}</ref>\n\n== History and location ==\nBecause of its location between the [[Tihamah]] coastal plain and Sana'a, this mountainous area has always been strategically important. A caravan stopping point during the [[Himyarite Kingdom]], the Haraz was later the stronghold of the [[Sulayhid dynasty]], which was established in Yemen in 1037. Then and subsequently the population have been [[Ism'aili]] [[Shia|Shi'ite]] [[Muslim]]s.\n\nHaraz is as famous for its fortified villages which cling to nearly inaccessible rocky peaks. Their imposing architecture meets two needs: defending the villagers, while leaving plenty of space for crops. Each town is built like a castle; the houses, themselves, form the wall, equipped with one or two easily defensible doors. Constructed from sandstone and basalt, the buildings are integrated into the landscape and it is difficult to tell where the rock and the village begins or ends. The mountain is divided into terraces of a few acres or more, separated by walls sometimes several meters high. On these terraced fields grow alfalfa for livestock, millet, lentils, large areas for coffee and [[Khat|qat]].\n\nWithin a day's journey are [[Bani Murrah|Banu Mora]] and other villages located on the ridge overlooking [[Manakhah]]. Manakhah is the heart of mountain range; a large town whose market attracts villagers from the entire neighbourhood. [[Al Hajjara]], to the west of Manakhah, is a walled village whose citadel was founded in the 12th century by the Sulayhids. From there, other villages are accessible, such as [[Bayt al-Qamus]]  and [[Bayt Shimran]]. The village of [[Hutaib]] is built on a platform of red sandstone, facing a view of terraced hills which host a score of villages. Here also is the mausoleum of the third Yemeni ''[[Da'i al-Mutlaq]]'' [[Hatim ibn Ibrahim]]. [[Mustaali|Bohras]] from [[India]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Madagascar]] and other countries gather here.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n== World Heritage Status ==\nThis area was added to the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage]] Tentative List on July 8, 2002, in the mixed (cultural and natural) category, as a site that has \"outstanding universal value\".<ref name=unesco/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Haraz 200612 Yemen-115 (353667843).jpg|A terraced mountain side in [[Al Mahwit Governorate]] near [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]] (the highest mountain in the Arabian Peninsula)\nFile:\u0645\u0646\u062a\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u062f\u0633\u064a\u0629 - panoramio.jpg|Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb is behind the mountain in the background, facing west of southern [[Sana'a]]\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (12633745063).jpg|Jabal Haraz terraces\nFile:Manakha 01.jpg|[[Manakhah]]\nFile:Haraz Mtns, Yemen (13970993973).jpg|Buildings at the base of a mountain\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (14616928081).jpg|\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ad Dahrah]], located in the Haraz, the stronghold of the Sulaihid dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive to this day\n* [[Geology of Yemen]]\n* [[Hajhir Mountains]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120922020555/http://www.lonelyplanet.com/yemen/the-harazmountains Lonely Planet]\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Jabal Haraz}}\n* [https://www.architecturerevived.com/architectural-beauty-out-of-poverty-jabal-haraz-yemen/ Architecture Revived: Architectural Beauty out of Poverty, Jabal Haraz Yemen]\n* [http://medomed.org/featured_item/jabal-bura-and-jabal-haraz-the-mountanous-cultural-landscape-of-yemen-yemen/ Med-O-Med: Cultural landscapes: Jabal Bura and Jabal Haraz, Yemen]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DcgXBQlPUJs Jabal Haraz] ([[YouTube]])\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qqJSqAjtbCA Yemen - Haraz Mountains]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mbooIXhPq-E Yemen 2008 Jebel Haraz]\n\n{{Tourist attractions in Yemen}}\n{{Mountains in the Arabian Peninsula}}\n\n[[Category:Jabal Haraz|*]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of mainland Yemen]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name              = Jabal Haraz\n| native_name       = {{lang|ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632}}\n| native_name_lang  = ar\n| photo             = Yemen (11462772954).jpg\n| photo_caption     = A building with terraces overlooks the side of one of the Haraz mountains\n| country           = {{YEM}}\n| region_type       = \n| region            = Asia\n| border            =\n| highest           = \n| elevation_m       = 3,000\n| highest_location  = \n| coordinates       = {{coord|15.1667|N|43.7500|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n| range_coordinates =\n| length_km         = \n| geology           =\n| period            =\n| orogeny           =\n| map               = Yemen#Middle East#Asia\n| map_image         = \n| map_caption       = \n}}\n\n'''Jabal Haraz''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632|Jabal \u1e24ar\u0101z}}) is a mountain region of [[Yemen]], between [[Sana'a]] and [[Al Hudaydah|Al-Hudaydah]]. In the 11th century, it was the stronghold of the [[Sulaihid State|Sulaihid]] dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive today.<ref name=unesco>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1722/ |title=Jabal Haraz |publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |date=2002-07-08 |access-date=2009-03-24}}</ref> They include [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]], the highest mountain in Yemen and the [[Arabian Peninsula]],<ref name=\"Laughlin2008\">{{cite book |last=McLaughlin |first=Daniel |title=Yemen |publisher=[[Bradt Travel Guides]] |chapter=1: Background |page=3 |isbn=978-1-8416-2212-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQvhZaEVzjcC&pg |year=2008}}</ref> and are considered part of the [[Sarawat Mountains|Sarat range]].<ref name=\"CookFarmer2013\">{{cite book |last1=Cook |first1=John |last2=Farmer |first2=G. Thomas |title=Climate Change Science: A Modern Synthesis |volume=1 \u2013 The Physical Climate |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer Science & Business Media]] |chapter=VI: Land and Its Climates |page=334 |isbn=9-4007-5757-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tbtEAAAAQBAJ&dq=sarawat+mountains&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2013-01-12}}</ref>\n\n== History and location ==\nBecause of its location between the [[Tihamah]] coastal plain and Sana'a, this mountainous area has always been strategically important. A caravan stopping point during the [[Himyarite Kingdom]], the Haraz was later the stronghold of the [[Sulayhid dynasty]], which was established in Yemen in 1037. Then and subsequently the population have been [[Ism'aili]] [[Shia|Shi'ite]] [[Muslim]]s.\n\nHaraz is as famous for its fortified villages which cling to nearly inaccessible rocky peaks. Their imposing architecture meets two needs: defending the villagers, while leaving plenty of space for crops. Each town is built like a castle; the houses, themselves, form the wall, equipped with one or two easily defensible doors. Constructed from sandstone and basalt, the buildings are integrated into the landscape and it is difficult to tell where the rock and the village begins or ends. The mountain is divided into terraces of a few acres or more, separated by walls sometimes several meters high. On these terraced fields grow alfalfa for livestock, millet, lentils, large areas for coffee and [[Khat|qat]].\n\nWithin a day's journey are [[Bani Murrah|Banu Mora]] and other villages located on the ridge overlooking [[Manakhah]]. Manakhah is the heart of mountain range; a large town whose market attracts villagers from the entire neighbourhood. [[Al Hajjara]], to the west of Manakhah, is a walled village whose citadel was founded in the 12th century by the Sulayhids. From there, other villages are accessible, such as [[Bayt al-Qamus]]  and [[Bayt Shimran]]. The village of [[Hutaib]] is built on a platform of red sandstone, facing a view of terraced hills which host a score of villages. Here also is the mausoleum of the third Yemeni ''[[Da'i al-Mutlaq]]'' [[Hatim ibn Ibrahim]]. [[Mustaali|Bohras]] from [[India]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Madagascar]] and other countries gather here.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n== World Heritage Status ==\nThis area was added to the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage]] Tentative List on July 8, 2002, in the mixed (cultural and natural) category, as a site that has \"outstanding universal value\".<ref name=unesco/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=packed>\nFile:\u0645\u0646\u062a\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u062f\u0633\u064a\u0629 - panoramio.jpg|[[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]], the highest mountain in the Arabian Peninsula, is behind the mountain in the background, facing west of southern [[Sana'a]]\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (12633745063).jpg|Jabal Haraz terraces\nFile:Manakha 01.jpg|[[Manakhah]]\nFile:Haraz Mtns, Yemen (13970993973).jpg|Buildings at the base of a mountain\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (14616928081).jpg|\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ad Dahrah]], located in the Haraz, the stronghold of the Sulaihid dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive to this day\n* [[Geology of Yemen]]\n* [[Hajhir Mountains]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120922020555/http://www.lonelyplanet.com/yemen/the-harazmountains Lonely Planet]\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Jabal Haraz}}\n* [https://www.architecturerevived.com/architectural-beauty-out-of-poverty-jabal-haraz-yemen/ Architecture Revived: Architectural Beauty out of Poverty, Jabal Haraz Yemen]\n* [http://medomed.org/featured_item/jabal-bura-and-jabal-haraz-the-mountanous-cultural-landscape-of-yemen-yemen/ Med-O-Med: Cultural landscapes: Jabal Bura and Jabal Haraz, Yemen]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/