{"title_page": "Sherman Miles", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Sherman Miles\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1882|12|5}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1966|10|7|1882|12|5}}\n|birth_place= [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"obit\">''[[The Washington Post]]'', obituary of Sherman Miles, October 11, 1966.</ref>\n|death_place= [[Beverly, Massachusetts]]\n|placeofburial= [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image=Sherman Miles.JPG\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1905&ndash;1946\n|rank=[[Major general (United States)|Major General]]\n|battles=[[World War I]]<br/>[[World War II]]\n|awards=[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]]\n|relations=[[Nelson A. Miles]], father\n|laterwork= [[Massachusetts House of Representatives|Member of the House of Representatives of Massachusetts, 1947&ndash;1952]]\n}}\n'''Sherman Miles''' (December 5, 1882<ref name=\"findagrave\">Find a grave: [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/42203106 Sherman Miles], URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref><ref name=\"beer\">Beer, Siegfried: \"Sherman Miles &ndash; vor und nach K\u00e4rnten 1919. Anmerkungen zu einer haupts\u00e4chlich nachrichtendienstlichen Karriere in der US-Armee\", pp.&nbsp;309&ndash;317 in Valentin, H.; Haiden, S.; Maier, B. (eds.): ''Die K\u00e4rntner Volksabstimmung 1920 und die Geschichtsforschung'', Verlag Johannes Heyn, Klagenfurt 2002. {{ISBN|3-85366-983-2}}.</ref> &ndash; October 7, 1966<ref name=\"obit\"/><ref name=\"findagrave\"/>) was a [[General]] of the [[U.S. Army]]. He was Chief of the [[Military Intelligence Division]] in 1941, when the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] happened.\n\n== Life ==\n\nMiles' parents were General [[Nelson A. Miles]] and Mary Hoyt Sherman Miles (niece to Civil War General [[William T. Sherman]]).<ref name=\"findagrave\"/> In 1901, he enrolled at the [[United States Military Academy]] at West Point, where he was graduated in 1905.<ref name=\"cullum5\">Cullum, George Washington: \"[http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOLUME_5_cullum.pdf Biographical register of the officers and graduates of the U. S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y. since its establishment in 1802. Supplement vol. 5 (1900-1910)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317190341/http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOLUME_5_cullum.pdf |date=2013-03-17 }}\". URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref> In 1909, he married Yulee Noble; they had two children.<ref name=\"beer\"/><ref name=\"arlington\">N.N.: ''[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/shermanm.htm Arlington National Cemetery Website: Sherman Miles]'', URL retrieved 2011-01-13.</ref>  He was a hereditary companion of the [[Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States]].\n\nDuring his military career, he held various posts as military attach\u00e9 in Europe. In 1940, he became the head of the [[Military Intelligence Division]] of the U.S. Army in [[George C. Marshall]]'s General Staff. Two months after the attack on Pearl Harbor on December 7, 1941, he was reassigned from that position to that of Commanding General of the First Service Command in Boston.\n\n== Early military career ==\n[[File:Sherman Miles, 1904.jpg|left|thumb|Miles, as a cadet]]\nMiles entered [[United States Military Academy|West Point]] on June 11, 1901, from where he graduated on June 13, 1905 and was commissioned as [[second lieutenant]], [[11th Armored Cavalry Regiment (United States)#2nd Squadron|11th Cavalry]]. With the 11th Cavalry, he was sent in 1906 to Cuba by then [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[William Howard Taft]]. Upon his return, he was transferred to the 3rd Field Artillery and promoted to [[first lieutenant]] in 1907.<ref name=\"cullum5\"/>\n\nFrom 1912 to 1914, he was [[military attach\u00e9]] on the [[Balkans]]. During [[World War I]], he served as military observer in Russia until 1916. He returned to the U.S. and was detailed to the General Staff Corps. In 1918, he was as an observer at the [[Meuse-Argonne Offensive|Argonne Offensive]]. As a General Staff member, he was temporarily promoted first to major in 1917, then to lieutenant colonel in 1918, and in 1919 to colonel.<ref name=\"cullum6B\">Cullum, George Washington: \"[http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOLUME_6B_cullum.pdf Biographical register of the officers and graduates of the U. S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y. since its establishment in 1802. Supplement vol. 6B (1910-1920)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531131358/http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOLUME_6B_cullum.pdf |date=2010-05-31 }}\". URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref>\n\n==Interwar period==\n\nImmediately after the armistice, Miles was assigned to the U.S. peace negotiation team. As a field member of the \"Coolidge Mission\" led by [[Archibald Cary Coolidge]], he traveled through former [[Austria-Hungary]] to assess the situation and to make demarcation recommendations for the benefit of the U.S. negotiators at the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919]].<ref name=\"cullum7\"/>\n\nOn January 27, 1919 Miles led the delegation of the Coolidge Mission which, on the way to Carinthia, visited the city of Marburg (today [[Maribor]] in [[Slovenia]]). Prior to the [[First World War]], Marburg had a population comprising 80% [[ethnic German|Austrian Germans]] and 20% Slovenes.<ref name=\"oshvdk\">Osterreicheische statistik Herausgegeben von der K.K. Statistischen Zentralkommission. neue folge 1. band. Ergebnisse der volkszahlung vom 31. dezember 1910. - Wien. aus der kaiserlich-koniglichen hof und staatsdruckerel 1917. in kommission bei karl gerold's sohn</ref> During Miles' visit, thousands of citizens of German ethnic origin gathered on the main city square, waving [[German Austria]] flags, many of which also decorated nearby buildings.<ref>{{cite web\n| url         = http://www.sistory.si/publikacije/prenos/?urn=SISTORY:ID:69\n| title       = Boj za Maribor\n| first       = Lojze\n| last        = Ude\n| authorlink  = Lojze Ude\n| year        = 1961\n| publisher   = Zgodovinski \u010dasopis\n| location    = Slovenia\n| page        = 139\n| language    = Slovenian\n| format      = pdf\n| accessdate  = January 11, 2011\n| quote       = Takoj po prihodu Ameri\u010danov so se na hi\u0161ah glavnih ulic,  kmalu na to pa po vsem mestu,  pojavile  \u010drno - rde\u010de - rumene trobojriice,  frankfurtarce.  Mariborsko nem\u0161ko me\u0161\u010danstvo,  pome\u0161ano z ljudmi,  ki so pri\u0161li od dmigod,  se je za\u010delo zbirati v neprestano nara\u0161\u010dajo\u010de sprevode.}}</ref> Slovenian military units commanded by [[Rudolf Maister]] killed between 11{{Citation needed|date=April 2012}} and 13<ref name=\"diepresse.com\">{{cite journal\n| date        = January 30, 2009\n| title       = J\u00e4nner 1919: Der Bluttag von Marburg a. d. Drau\n| journal      = Die Presse\n| language     = German\n| accessdate   = January 5, 2011\n| url          = http://diepresse.com/home/politik/zeitgeschichte/448662/Jaenner-1919_Der-Bluttag-von-Marburg-a-d-Drau\n| archiveurl   = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fdiepresse.com%2Fhome%2Fpolitik%2Fzeitgeschichte%2F448662%2FJaenner-1919_Der-Bluttag-von-Marburg-a-d-Drau&date=2011-01-05\n| archivedate  = January 5, 2011\n| quote        = Eine Salve nach der anderen feuerten die Soldaten in die nichtsahnende, wehr- und waffenlose Volksmenge, .... 13 Tote und etwa 60 Verwundete...\n}}</ref> German civilian protesters in a central Maribor square, during event known as [[Marburg's Bloody Sunday]].\n\nRegarding [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthia]], the Coolidge Mission focused on where to draw the future border between the newly formed [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]] and [[Austria]]. The U.S. position before the Paris conference favored, like the British and French, a separation along ethnographic lines, i.e., a border along the river [[Drava]] (German: ''Drau''), which would have split the economic and geographic region of the [[Klagenfurt]] basin. The Yugoslavs also favored this solution. Miles became instrumental in reversing this position.\n\nIn his field travels, he learned that many of the Slovene speakers in the region actually preferred to belong to Austria and had closer economic ties to the Klagenfurt area than to Slovenia. He proposed, instead, a border along the [[Karawanks]] further south. Through his reports, he was able to convince his superiors that the best way to settle the question was through self-determination. The U.S. team eventually convinced the British and French delegations in Paris, and finally it was decided that the area should remain undivided, and that the question of whether it should henceforth belong to Austria or to Yugoslavia was to be decided by a vote among the population of the area. In the [[Carinthian Plebiscite|plebiscite held on October 10, 1920]], the population voted for Miles' border proposal.<ref name=\"ehrfeld\">Fr\u00e4ss-Ehrfeld, Claudia: \"[https://digital.lib.washington.edu/ojs/index.php/ssj/article/viewFile/3612/3025 The Role of the United States of America and the Carinthian Question, 1918-1920]\", ''Slovene Studies '''8'''/1 (1986)'', pp.&nbsp;7&ndash;13. URL retrieved 2011-01-13.</ref><ref name=\"frus1919_12\">U.S. Department of State, ''[http://digicoll.library.wisc.edu/cgi-bin/FRUS/FRUS-idx?type=turn&entity=FRUS.FRUS1919Parisv12.p0009&id=FRUS.FRUS1919Parisv12&isize=text Papers relating to the foreign relations of the United States, The Paris Peace Conference, 1919, vol XII]''. URL retrieved 2011-01-11.</ref><ref name=\"street\">In Klagenfurt, a street was named after Miles in 1970. See ''Carinthia I: Mitteilungen des Geschichtsvereins f\u00fcr K\u00e4rnten, Vol. 194'', 2004, p.&nbsp;741. Also in the city of [[V\u00f6lkermarkt]] in Carinthia, a street is named after Sherman Miles.[https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Sherman+Miles-Stra%C3%9Fe,+V%C3%B6lkermarkt,+%C3%96sterreich&sll=46.616667,14.3&sspn=0.220256,0.404434&ie=UTF8&hq=&hnear=Sherman+Miles-Stra%C3%9Fe,+9100+V%C3%B6lkermarkt,+K%C3%A4rnten,+Austria&t=h&z=17].</ref>\n\nWhen these post-war assignments terminated, he returned to the U.S. and reverted to the rank of major in 1920.<ref name=\"cullum7\">Cullum, George Washington: \"[http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOLUME_7_cullum.pdf Biographical register of the officers and graduates of the U. S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y. since its establishment in 1802. Supplement vol. 7 (1920-1930)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317190955/http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOLUME_7_cullum.pdf |date=2013-03-17 }}\". URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref> In the 1920s, he attended various military schools ([[United States Army War College|Army War College]] 1921-22, Coast Artillery School 1925-26, General Staff School 1926-27) and was posted to various units in the [[U.S. Army Coast Artillery Corps|Coast Artillery]] and in the [[Field Artillery Branch (United States)|Field Artillery]] until the late 1930s.\n\nFrom 1922 to 1925 he was military attach\u00e9 at Constantinople in Turkey,<ref name=\"cullum7\"/> and was sent in 1924 to Teheran to investigate the murder of U.S. Vice Consul [[Robert Whitney Imbrie]] there.<ref name=\"zirinsky\">Zirinsky, M.: \"[http://scholarworks.boisestate.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1000&context=history_facpubs Blood, Power, and Hypocrisy: The Murder of Robert Imbrie and American Relations with Pahlavi Iran, 1924]\", in ''International Journal of Middle East Studies '''18'''.3 (1986)'', pp.&nbsp;275-292. URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref> Miles was promoted to lieutenant colonel in the Regular Army in 1929 and to colonel in 1935.\n\nFrom September 1, 1938 on, he was commanding school troops at the [[United States Army Field Artillery School]] at [[Fort Sill]], Oklahoma.<ref name=\"cullum8\">Cullum, George Washington: \"[http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOL8_PART0002.PDF Biographical register of the officers and graduates of the U. S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y. since its establishment in 1802. Supplement vol. 8 (1930-1940)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720103013/http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOL8_PART0002.PDF |date=2011-07-20 }}\". URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref>\n\nOn September 1, 1939, he was promoted to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]] and served as military attach\u00e9 in [[London]] for half a year before returning to the U.S., where he became a senior member of Army Chief of Staff General [[George C. Marshall]]'s general staff in 1941.  Miles was assigned as \"Assistant Chief of Staff G-2\", i.e., the head of the [[Military Intelligence Division]] (MID).<ref name=\"cullum9\">Cullum, George Washington: \"[http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOL9_PART0001.PDF Biographical register of the officers and graduates of the U. S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y. since its establishment in 1802. Supplement vol. 9 (1940-1950)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720103455/http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOL9_PART0001.PDF |date=2011-07-20 }}\". URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref>\n\nThe MID greatly expanded during his time as G-2, but, as Miles put it, \"always in a piecemeal manner\".<ref name=\"finnegan\">Finnegan, John Patrick: ''[http://www.history.army.mil/books/Lineage/mi/mi-fm.htm Military Intelligence]'', Center for Military History, U.S. Army 1998, CMH pub 60-13, here ''[http://www.history.army.mil/books/Lineage/mi/ch4.htm Chapter 4: Military Intelligence in Crisis]''. URLs retrieved 2011-01-14.</ref> Qualified cryptography personnel were scarce, and Japanese-speaking personnel were also hard to come by.  Miles' suggestions to set up an [[espionage]] service were ignored until June 1941,<ref name=\"finnegan\"/><ref name=\"life\">''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', Dec 2, 1940 issue, p.&nbsp;94: ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=O0oEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA94&ots=57DHOUFRq5&pg=PA94#v=onepage These are U.S. Army's six foremost Generals]'', wrote even that \"spies are considered un-American\". URL retrieved 2011-01-14.</ref> when U.S. President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] appointed [[William J. Donovan]] as [[Office of the Coordinator of Information|Coordinator of Information]]. Donovan's unit would eventually become the [[Office of Strategic Services|OSS]], but it was independent from the MID and needed time to mature, which made for a difficult collaboration (if not to say a rivalry) between the MID and the OSS from the beginning and continuing throughout the war.<ref name=\"finnegan\"/>\n\n==World War II==\n\nThe attack on Pearl Harbor ended Miles' career in the General Staff.<ref name=\"casey\">[[Richard Casey, Baron Casey|Casey, Richard Gardiner]]: ''A delicate mission: the Washington diaries of R.G. Casey, 1940-42'', {{ISBN|0-642-27662-5}}, p. 214: \"25 December 1941 ... Amongst the various heads that have been rolled in the dust has been that of General Sherman Miles (U.S. Military Intelligence)... General Raymond Lee (late U.S. Military Attach\u00e9 in London) has taken Sherman Miles' place.\"</ref> MID very much relied on intercepted Japanese radio messages. The decoded \"[[Magic (cryptography)|Magic]]\" messages were top-secret and circulated only in a very select circle of ten people comprising the General Staffs of the Army and the Navy, the Secretary of War, and the President.<ref name=\"congress_180\">U.S. Congress, Joint Committee on the Investigation of the Pearl Harbor Attack, ''[http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/pha/congress/part_0.html Investigation of the Pearl Harbor Attack], U.S. GPO, 1946, here \"[http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/pha/congress/part_4.html#179 Chapter IV: Responsibilities in Washington], p.&nbsp;180, \"Policy with respect to dissemination of Magic\". URLs retrieved 2011-01-18.</ref> No coherent analysis of these messages was done.<ref name=\"finnegan\"/> The warnings that the General Staff sent to Hawaii failed to stress the urgency because MID themselves did not consider the contents of the \"Magic\" intercepts received prior to the attack as particularly significant at that time.<ref name=\"congress2\">Congress of the United States, 79th Congress, 1st session: ''[https://archive.org/stream/pearlharborattac02unit#page/794/mode/2up Pearl Harbor attack: Hearings before the Joint Committee on the investigation of the Pearl Harbor attack]'', U.S. GPO 1946; testimony of Gen. Miles on November 29, 1945: p.&nbsp;794ff.</ref> In addition, communication channels in the U.S. military were convoluted due to the split commands of Army and Navy, each with their own intelligence branch,<ref name=\"congress_concl\">Congress of the United States, 79th Congress, 2nd session: ''[http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/pha/congress/part_0.html Investigation of the Pearl Harbor attack: Report the Joint Committee on the investigation of the Pearl Harbor attack]'', U.S. GPO 1946; here in particular [http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/pha/congress/part_5.html#252 Part V: Conclusion and recommendations], p.&nbsp;253.</ref> and the last message to Hawaii before the attack was delayed and was decoded at Hawaii only after the attack had already begun.<ref name=\"congress_180\" /><ref name=\"armyboard\">U.S. Army Pearl Harbor Board:''[http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/pha/army/chap_0.html Report of the Army Pearl Harbor Board]'', U.A. Army, 1944, here [http://ibiblio.org/pha/pha/army/chap_3c.html#138 Chapter 3C: Critical Period: October 1 to December 7, 1941]\", p.&nbsp;138ff, \"December 7, 1941 Message\". URLs retrieved 2011-01-18.</ref>\n\nTen days after the attack on Pearl Harbor, Miles was sent on an inspection tour through South America to survey installations there and to make recommendations for military assistance to the Latin American countries;<ref name=\"conn\">Conn, Stetson; Fairchild, Byron: ''[http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/Framework/index.htm#contents The Framework of Hemisphere Defense]'', Center of Military History, U.S. Army 1960, CMH pub 4-1; \"[http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/Framework/ch08.htm Chapter VIII: General Military Relations With Latin America]\", p.&nbsp;200ff. URL retrieved 2011-01-17.</ref> Acting Assistant Chief of Staff G-2 became Brigadier General Raymond E. Lee.<ref name=\"mercado\">Mercado, Stephen C.: \"[https://www.cia.gov/library/center-for-the-study-of-intelligence/kent-csi/vol45no5/html/v45i5a04p.htm FBIS Against the Axis, 1941-1945 (U)]\", ''Studies in Intelligence Fall/Winter 2001'', issue 11, pp.&nbsp;33&ndash;43. CIA, 2001. Mentions on page 40 and in footnote 25 that Raymond E. Lee was Acting ACoS G-2 on December 26, 1941. URL retrieved 2011-01-17.</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 1942, Miles was promoted to [[major general]] and then reassigned as commanding general of the First Service Command (later re-designated as the First Service Corps) in Boston.  The Service Commands, sub-entities of the [[Army Service Forces]], were supporting services for the fighting forces.<ref name=\"millet1954\">Millet, John D.: ''[http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/ASF/index.htm#contents The Organization and Role of the Army Service Forces]'', Center of Military History, U.S. Army, 1954, CMH pub. 3-1. Here \"[http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/ASF/chapter23.htm Chapter XXIII: The Management of the Army Services Forces]\", p.&nbsp;370. URLs retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref>\n\nMiles served in this position for the duration of the war and retired from the Army on February 28, 1946.  Upon his retirement, Miles received the [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]], the Army's highest non-combat decoration, in recognition of his wartime service.<ref name=\"cullum9\"/><ref name=\"hewes\">After Marshall's reorganization of the General Staff, Maj. Gen. [[George V. Strong]] was G-2 from May 5, 1942 to Feb 6, 1944; then Maj. Gen. [[Clayton Bissell]] held that post until January 1946. C.f. Hewes, James E. Jr.: ''[http://www.history.army.mil/books/root/index.htm#contents From Root to McNamara: Army Organization and Administration]'', Center of Military History, U.S. Army 1975, CMH pub 40-1; [http://www.history.army.mil/books/root/appB.htm Appendix B: Principal Officials of the War Department and Department of the Army, 1900-1963], p.&nbsp;389, and \"[http://www.history.army.mil/books/root/chapter3.htm#b3 Chapter III: Changes in the Marshall organization]\", p.&nbsp;107. URLs retrieved 2011-01-13.</ref>\n\n==Later life==\n\nAfter his retirement from the Army, Miles served as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[Massachusetts House of Representatives]] from 1947 to 1952.<ref name=\"publicMA\">Hayden, I.N., Grove, L.R.: ''[https://archive.org/stream/publicofficersof19511952bost#page/236/mode/2up Public officers of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts (1951-1952)]'', p.&nbsp;237. URL retrieved 2011-01-13.</ref> In 1948, he wrote the article \"Pearl Harbor in Retrospect\" in the July 1948 issue of ''[[The Atlantic]]'', in which he gave his perspective on the events just prior to the attack.<ref name=\"atlantic\">Miles, Sherman: \"[https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1969/12/pearl-harbor-in-retrospect/5485/ Pearl Harbor in Retrospect]\", ''The Atlantic'', July 1948. URL retrieved 2011-01-13.</ref>\n\nAfter the death of his wife Yulee in 1953, he married Edith Lawrence Coolidge, widow of [[Harold Jefferson Coolidge, Sr.]], in 1954.<ref name=\"beer\"/>\n\nHe died at the hospital in [[Beverly, Massachusetts]] after long illness<ref name=\"obit\"/> and was buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]] in the [[Miles Mausoleum]] on October 12, 1966.<ref name=\"arlington\"/>\n\n==Memberships==\nGeneral Miles joined the [[Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States]] as a Second Class Companion and, upon his father's death, became a Companion of the First Class.\n\n==Military awards==\n\nArmy General Staff Identification Badge\n{|\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Army of Cuban Pacification ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army of Cuban Pacification Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Mexican Border Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Mexican Border Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=World War I Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[World War I Victory Medal (United States)|World War I Victory Medal]] with three battle clasps\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Army of Occupation of Germany ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army of Occupation of Germany Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=American Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[American Defense Service Medal]] with Foreign Service Clasp\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=American Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[American Campaign Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=World War II Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[World War II Victory Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Legion Honneur Chevalier ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Legion of Honor|Chevalier of the Legion of Honor]]\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Henry L. Shattuck]]\t\n| title=Member of the [[Massachusetts House of Representatives]] from the 5th Suffolk District\n| years=1947 \u2013 1953\n| after=[[John Yerxa]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miles, Sherman}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Republicans]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Sherman Miles\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1882|12|5}}\n|death_date= {{Death date and age|1966|10|7|1882|12|5}}\n|birth_place= [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"obit\">''[[The Washington Post]]'', obituary of Sherman Miles, October 11, 1966.</ref>\n|death_place= [[Beverly, Massachusetts]]\n|placeofburial= [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image=Sherman Miles.JPG\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1905&ndash;1946\n|rank=[[Major general (United States)|Major General]]\n|battles=[[World War I]]<br/>[[World War II]]\n|awards=[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]]\n|relations=[[Nelson A. Miles]], father\n|laterwork= [[Massachusetts House of Representatives|Member of the House of Representatives of Massachusetts, 1947&ndash;1952]]\n}}\n'''Sherman Miles''' (December 5, 1882<ref name=\"findagrave\">Find a grave: [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/42203106 Sherman Miles], URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref><ref name=\"beer\">Beer, Siegfried: \"Sherman Miles &ndash; vor und nach K\u00e4rnten 1919. Anmerkungen zu einer haupts\u00e4chlich nachrichtendienstlichen Karriere in der US-Armee\", pp.&nbsp;309&ndash;317 in Valentin, H.; Haiden, S.; Maier, B. (eds.): ''Die K\u00e4rntner Volksabstimmung 1920 und die Geschichtsforschung'', Verlag Johannes Heyn, Klagenfurt 2002. {{ISBN|3-85366-983-2}}.</ref> &ndash; October 7, 1966<ref name=\"obit\"/><ref name=\"findagrave\"/>) was a [[General]] of the [[U.S. Army]]. He was Chief of the [[Military Intelligence Division]] in 1941, when the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] happened.\n\n== Life ==\n\nMiles' parents were General [[Nelson A. Miles]] and Mary Hoyt Sherman Miles (niece to Civil War General [[William T. Sherman]]).<ref name=\"findagrave\"/> In 1901, he enrolled at the [[United States Military Academy]] at West Point, where he was graduated in 1905.<ref name=\"cullum5\">Cullum, George Washington: \"[http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOLUME_5_cullum.pdf Biographical register of the officers and graduates of the U. S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y. since its establishment in 1802. Supplement vol. 5 (1900-1910)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317190341/http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOLUME_5_cullum.pdf |date=2013-03-17 }}\". URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref> In 1909, he married Yulee Noble; they had two children.<ref name=\"beer\"/><ref name=\"arlington\">N.N.: ''[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/shermanm.htm Arlington National Cemetery Website: Sherman Miles]'', URL retrieved 2011-01-13.</ref>  He was a hereditary companion of the [[Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States]].\n\nDuring his military career, he held various posts as military attach\u00e9 in Europe. In 1940, he became the head of the [[Military Intelligence Division]] of the U.S. Army in [[George C. Marshall]]'s General Staff. Two months after the attack on Pearl Harbor on December 7, 1941, he was reassigned from that position to that of Commanding General of the First Service Command in Boston.\n\n== Early military career ==\n[[File:Sherman Miles, 1904.jpg|left|thumb|Miles, as a cadet]]\nMiles entered [[United States Military Academy|West Point]] on June 11, 1901, from where he graduated on June 13, 1905 and was commissioned as [[second lieutenant]], [[11th Armored Cavalry Regiment (United States)#2nd Squadron|11th Cavalry]]. With the 11th Cavalry, he was sent in 1906 to Cuba by then [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[William Howard Taft]]. Upon his return, he was transferred to the 3rd Field Artillery and promoted to [[first lieutenant]] in 1907.<ref name=\"cullum5\"/>\n\nFrom 1912 to 1914, he was [[military attach\u00e9]] on the [[Balkans]]. During [[World War I]], he served as military observer in Russia until 1916. He returned to the U.S. and was detailed to the General Staff Corps. In 1918, he was as an observer at the [[Meuse-Argonne Offensive|Argonne Offensive]]. As a General Staff member, he was temporarily promoted first to major in 1917, then to lieutenant colonel in 1918, and in 1919 to colonel.<ref name=\"cullum6B\">Cullum, George Washington: \"[http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOLUME_6B_cullum.pdf Biographical register of the officers and graduates of the U. S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y. since its establishment in 1802. Supplement vol. 6B (1910-1920)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531131358/http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOLUME_6B_cullum.pdf |date=2010-05-31 }}\". URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref>\n\n==Interwar period==\n\nImmediately after the armistice, Miles was assigned to the U.S. peace negotiation team. As a field member of the \"Coolidge Mission\" led by [[Archibald Cary Coolidge]], he traveled through former [[Austria-Hungary]] to assess the situation and to make demarcation recommendations for the benefit of the U.S. negotiators at the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919]].<ref name=\"cullum7\"/>\n\nOn January 27, 1919 Miles led the delegation of the Coolidge Mission which, on the way to Carinthia, visited the city of Marburg (today [[Maribor]] in [[Slovenia]]). Prior to the [[First World War]], Marburg had a population comprising 80% [[ethnic German|Austrian Germans]] and 20% Slovenes.<ref name=\"oshvdk\">Osterreicheische statistik Herausgegeben von der K.K. Statistischen Zentralkommission. neue folge 1. band. Ergebnisse der volkszahlung vom 31. dezember 1910. - Wien. aus der kaiserlich-koniglichen hof und staatsdruckerel 1917. in kommission bei karl gerold's sohn</ref> During Miles' visit, thousands of citizens of German ethnic origin gathered on the main city square, waving [[German Austria]] flags, many of which also decorated nearby buildings.<ref>{{cite web\n| url         = http://www.sistory.si/publikacije/prenos/?urn=SISTORY:ID:69\n| title       = Boj za Maribor\n| first       = Lojze\n| last        = Ude\n| authorlink  = Lojze Ude\n| year        = 1961\n| publisher   = Zgodovinski \u010dasopis\n| location    = Slovenia\n| page        = 139\n| language    = Slovenian\n| format      = pdf\n| accessdate  = January 11, 2011\n| quote       = Takoj po prihodu Ameri\u010danov so se na hi\u0161ah glavnih ulic,  kmalu na to pa po vsem mestu,  pojavile  \u010drno - rde\u010de - rumene trobojriice,  frankfurtarce.  Mariborsko nem\u0161ko me\u0161\u010danstvo,  pome\u0161ano z ljudmi,  ki so pri\u0161li od dmigod,  se je za\u010delo zbirati v neprestano nara\u0161\u010dajo\u010de sprevode.}}</ref> Slovenian military units commanded by [[Rudolf Maister]] killed between 11{{Citation needed|date=April 2012}} and 13<ref name=\"diepresse.com\">{{cite journal\n| date        = January 30, 2009\n| title       = J\u00e4nner 1919: Der Bluttag von Marburg a. d. Drau\n| journal      = Die Presse\n| language     = German\n| accessdate   = January 5, 2011\n| url          = http://diepresse.com/home/politik/zeitgeschichte/448662/Jaenner-1919_Der-Bluttag-von-Marburg-a-d-Drau\n| archiveurl   = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fdiepresse.com%2Fhome%2Fpolitik%2Fzeitgeschichte%2F448662%2FJaenner-1919_Der-Bluttag-von-Marburg-a-d-Drau&date=2011-01-05\n| archivedate  = January 5, 2011\n| quote        = Eine Salve nach der anderen feuerten die Soldaten in die nichtsahnende, wehr- und waffenlose Volksmenge, .... 13 Tote und etwa 60 Verwundete...\n}}</ref> German civilian protesters in a central Maribor square, during event known as [[Marburg's Bloody Sunday]].\n\nRegarding [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthia]], the Coolidge Mission focused on where to draw the future border between the newly formed [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]] and [[Austria]]. The U.S. position before the Paris conference favored, like the British and French, a separation along ethnographic lines, i.e., a border along the river [[Drava]] (German: ''Drau''), which would have split the economic and geographic region of the [[Klagenfurt]] basin. The Yugoslavs also favored this solution. Miles became instrumental in reversing this position.\n\nIn his field travels, he learned that many of the Slovene speakers in the region actually preferred to belong to Austria and had closer economic ties to the Klagenfurt area than to Slovenia. He proposed, instead, a border along the [[Karawanks]] further south. Through his reports, he was able to convince his superiors that the best way to settle the question was through self-determination. The U.S. team eventually convinced the British and French delegations in Paris, and finally it was decided that the area should remain undivided, and that the question of whether it should henceforth belong to Austria or to Yugoslavia was to be decided by a vote among the population of the area. In the [[Carinthian Plebiscite|plebiscite held on October 10, 1920]], the population voted for Miles' border proposal.<ref name=\"ehrfeld\">Fr\u00e4ss-Ehrfeld, Claudia: \"[https://digital.lib.washington.edu/ojs/index.php/ssj/article/viewFile/3612/3025 The Role of the United States of America and the Carinthian Question, 1918-1920]\", ''Slovene Studies '''8'''/1 (1986)'', pp.&nbsp;7&ndash;13. URL retrieved 2011-01-13.</ref><ref name=\"frus1919_12\">U.S. Department of State, ''[http://digicoll.library.wisc.edu/cgi-bin/FRUS/FRUS-idx?type=turn&entity=FRUS.FRUS1919Parisv12.p0009&id=FRUS.FRUS1919Parisv12&isize=text Papers relating to the foreign relations of the United States, The Paris Peace Conference, 1919, vol XII]''. URL retrieved 2011-01-11.</ref><ref name=\"street\">In Klagenfurt, a street was named after Miles in 1970. See ''Carinthia I: Mitteilungen des Geschichtsvereins f\u00fcr K\u00e4rnten, Vol. 194'', 2004, p.&nbsp;741. Also in the city of [[V\u00f6lkermarkt]] in Carinthia, a street is named after Sherman Miles.[https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&q=Sherman+Miles-Stra%C3%9Fe,+V%C3%B6lkermarkt,+%C3%96sterreich&sll=46.616667,14.3&sspn=0.220256,0.404434&ie=UTF8&hq=&hnear=Sherman+Miles-Stra%C3%9Fe,+9100+V%C3%B6lkermarkt,+K%C3%A4rnten,+Austria&t=h&z=17].</ref>\n\nWhen these post-war assignments terminated, he returned to the U.S. and reverted to the rank of major in 1920.<ref name=\"cullum7\">Cullum, George Washington: \"[http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOLUME_7_cullum.pdf Biographical register of the officers and graduates of the U. S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y. since its establishment in 1802. Supplement vol. 7 (1920-1930)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317190955/http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOLUME_7_cullum.pdf |date=2013-03-17 }}\". URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref> In the 1920s, he attended various military schools ([[United States Army War College|Army War College]] 1921-22, Coast Artillery School 1925-26, General Staff School 1926-27) and was posted to various units in the [[U.S. Army Coast Artillery Corps|Coast Artillery]] and in the [[Field Artillery Branch (United States)|Field Artillery]] until the late 1930s.\n\nFrom 1922 to 1925 he was military attach\u00e9 at Constantinople in Turkey,<ref name=\"cullum7\"/> and was sent in 1924 to Teheran to investigate the murder of U.S. Vice Consul [[Robert Whitney Imbrie]] there.<ref name=\"zirinsky\">Zirinsky, M.: \"[http://scholarworks.boisestate.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1000&context=history_facpubs Blood, Power, and Hypocrisy: The Murder of Robert Imbrie and American Relations with Pahlavi Iran, 1924]\", in ''International Journal of Middle East Studies '''18'''.3 (1986)'', pp.&nbsp;275-292. URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref> Miles was promoted to lieutenant colonel in the Regular Army in 1929 and to colonel in 1935.\n\nFrom September 1, 1938 on, he was commanding school troops at the [[United States Army Field Artillery School]] at [[Fort Sill]], Oklahoma.<ref name=\"cullum8\">Cullum, George Washington: \"[http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOL8_PART0002.PDF Biographical register of the officers and graduates of the U. S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y. since its establishment in 1802. Supplement vol. 8 (1930-1940)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720103013/http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOL8_PART0002.PDF |date=2011-07-20 }}\". URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref>\n\nOn September 1, 1939, he was promoted to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]] and served as military attach\u00e9 in [[London]] for half a year before returning to the U.S., where he became a senior member of Army Chief of Staff General [[George C. Marshall]]'s general staff in 1941.  Miles was assigned as \"Assistant Chief of Staff G-2\", i.e., the head of the [[Military Intelligence Division]] (MID).<ref name=\"cullum9\">Cullum, George Washington: \"[http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOL9_PART0001.PDF Biographical register of the officers and graduates of the U. S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y. since its establishment in 1802. Supplement vol. 9 (1940-1950)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720103455/http://digital-library.usma.edu/libmedia/archives/cullum/VOL9_PART0001.PDF |date=2011-07-20 }}\". URL retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref>\n\nThe MID greatly expanded during his time as G-2, but, as Miles put it, \"always in a piecemeal manner\".<ref name=\"finnegan\">Finnegan, John Patrick: ''[http://www.history.army.mil/books/Lineage/mi/mi-fm.htm Military Intelligence]'', Center for Military History, U.S. Army 1998, CMH pub 60-13, here ''[http://www.history.army.mil/books/Lineage/mi/ch4.htm Chapter 4: Military Intelligence in Crisis]''. URLs retrieved 2011-01-14.</ref> Qualified cryptography personnel were scarce, and Japanese-speaking personnel were also hard to come by.  Miles' suggestions to set up an [[espionage]] service were ignored until June 1941,<ref name=\"finnegan\"/><ref name=\"life\">''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', Dec 2, 1940 issue, p.&nbsp;94: ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=O0oEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA94&ots=57DHOUFRq5&pg=PA94#v=onepage These are U.S. Army's six foremost Generals]'', wrote even that \"spies are considered un-American\". URL retrieved 2011-01-14.</ref> when U.S. President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] appointed [[William J. Donovan]] as [[Office of the Coordinator of Information|Coordinator of Information]]. Donovan's unit would eventually become the [[Office of Strategic Services|OSS]], but it was independent from the MID and needed time to mature, which made for a difficult collaboration (if not to say a rivalry) between the MID and the OSS from the beginning and continuing throughout the war.<ref name=\"finnegan\"/>\n\n==World War II==\n\nThe attack on Pearl Harbor ended Miles' career in the General Staff.<ref name=\"casey\">[[Richard Casey, Baron Casey|Casey, Richard Gardiner]]: ''A delicate mission: the Washington diaries of R.G. Casey, 1940-42'', {{ISBN|0-642-27662-5}}, p. 214: \"25 December 1941 ... Amongst the various heads that have been rolled in the dust has been that of General Sherman Miles (U.S. Military Intelligence)... General Raymond Lee (late U.S. Military Attach\u00e9 in London) has taken Sherman Miles' place.\"</ref> MID very much relied on intercepted Japanese radio messages. The decoded \"[[Magic (cryptography)|Magic]]\" messages were top-secret and circulated only in a very select circle of ten people comprising the General Staffs of the Army and the Navy, the Secretary of War, and the President.<ref name=\"congress_180\">U.S. Congress, Joint Committee on the Investigation of the Pearl Harbor Attack, ''[http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/pha/congress/part_0.html Investigation of the Pearl Harbor Attack], U.S. GPO, 1946, here \"[http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/pha/congress/part_4.html#179 Chapter IV: Responsibilities in Washington], p.&nbsp;180, \"Policy with respect to dissemination of Magic\". URLs retrieved 2011-01-18.</ref>  No coherent analysis of these messages was done.<ref name=\"finnegan\"/> The warnings that the General Staff sent to Hawaii failed to stress the urgency because MID themselves did not consider the contents of the \"Magic\" intercepts received prior to the attack as particularly significant at that time.<ref name=\"congress2\">Congress of the United States, 79th Congress, 1st session: ''[https://archive.org/stream/pearlharborattac02unit#page/794/mode/2up Pearl Harbor attack: Hearings before the Joint Committee on the investigation of the Pearl Harbor attack]'', U.S. GPO 1946; testimony of Gen. Miles on November 29, 1945: p.&nbsp;794ff.</ref> In addition, communication channels in the U.S. military were convoluted due to the split commands of Army and Navy, each with their own intelligence branch,<ref name=\"congress_concl\">Congress of the United States, 79th Congress, 2nd session: ''[http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/pha/congress/part_0.html Investigation of the Pearl Harbor attack: Report the Joint Committee on the investigation of the Pearl Harbor attack]'', U.S. GPO 1946; here in particular [http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/pha/congress/part_5.html#252 Part V: Conclusion and recommendations], p.&nbsp;253.</ref> and the last message to Hawaii before the attack was delayed and was decoded at Hawaii only after the attack had already begun.<ref name=\"congress_180\">U.S. Congress, Joint Committee on the Investigation of the Pearl Harbor Attack, ''[http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/pha/congress/part_0.html Investigation of the Pearl Harbor Attack], U.S. GPO, 1946, here \"[http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/pha/congress/part_4.html#222 Chapter IV: Responsibilities in Washington], p.&nbsp;222ff, \"'One O'Clock' and final code destruction messages\". URLs retrieved 2011-01-18.</ref><ref name=\"armyboard\">U.S. Army Pearl Harbor Board:''[http://www.ibiblio.org/pha/pha/army/chap_0.html Report of the Army Pearl Harbor Board]'', U.A. Army, 1944, here [http://ibiblio.org/pha/pha/army/chap_3c.html#138 Chapter 3C: Critical Period: October 1 to December 7, 1941]\", p.&nbsp;138ff, \"December 7, 1941 Message\". URLs retrieved 2011-01-18.</ref>\n\nTen days after the attack on Pearl Harbor, Miles was sent on an inspection tour through South America to survey installations there and to make recommendations for military assistance to the Latin American countries;<ref name=\"conn\">Conn, Stetson; Fairchild, Byron: ''[http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/Framework/index.htm#contents The Framework of Hemisphere Defense]'', Center of Military History, U.S. Army 1960, CMH pub 4-1; \"[http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/Framework/ch08.htm Chapter VIII: General Military Relations With Latin America]\", p.&nbsp;200ff. URL retrieved 2011-01-17.</ref> Acting Assistant Chief of Staff G-2 became Brigadier General Raymond E. Lee.<ref name=\"mercado\">Mercado, Stephen C.: \"[https://www.cia.gov/library/center-for-the-study-of-intelligence/kent-csi/vol45no5/html/v45i5a04p.htm FBIS Against the Axis, 1941-1945 (U)]\", ''Studies in Intelligence Fall/Winter 2001'', issue 11, pp.&nbsp;33&ndash;43. CIA, 2001. Mentions on page 40 and in footnote 25 that Raymond E. Lee was Acting ACoS G-2 on December 26, 1941. URL retrieved 2011-01-17.</ref>\n\nOn January 28, 1942, Miles was promoted to [[major general]] and then reassigned as commanding general of the First Service Command (later re-designated as the First Service Corps) in Boston.  The Service Commands, sub-entities of the [[Army Service Forces]], were supporting services for the fighting forces.<ref name=\"millet1954\">Millet, John D.: ''[http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/ASF/index.htm#contents The Organization and Role of the Army Service Forces]'', Center of Military History, U.S. Army, 1954, CMH pub. 3-1. Here \"[http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/ASF/chapter23.htm Chapter XXIII: The Management of the Army Services Forces]\", p.&nbsp;370. URLs retrieved 2011-01-12.</ref>\n\nMiles served in this position for the duration of the war and retired from the Army on February 28, 1946.  Upon his retirement, Miles received the [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Distinguished Service Medal]], the Army's highest non-combat decoration, in recognition of his wartime service.<ref name=\"cullum9\"/><ref name=\"hewes\">After Marshall's reorganization of the General Staff, Maj. Gen. [[George V. Strong]] was G-2 from May 5, 1942 to Feb 6, 1944; then Maj. Gen. [[Clayton Bissell]] held that post until January 1946. C.f. Hewes, James E. Jr.: ''[http://www.history.army.mil/books/root/index.htm#contents From Root to McNamara: Army Organization and Administration]'', Center of Military History, U.S. Army 1975, CMH pub 40-1; [http://www.history.army.mil/books/root/appB.htm Appendix B: Principal Officials of the War Department and Department of the Army, 1900-1963], p.&nbsp;389, and \"[http://www.history.army.mil/books/root/chapter3.htm#b3 Chapter III: Changes in the Marshall organization]\", p.&nbsp;107. URLs retrieved 2011-01-13.</ref>\n\n==Later life==\n\nAfter his retirement from the Army, Miles served as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[Massachusetts House of Representatives]] from 1947 to 1952.<ref name=\"publicMA\">Hayden, I.N., Grove, L.R.: ''[https://archive.org/stream/publicofficersof19511952bost#page/236/mode/2up Public officers of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts (1951-1952)]'', p.&nbsp;237. URL retrieved 2011-01-13.</ref> In 1948, he wrote the article \"Pearl Harbor in Retrospect\" in the July 1948 issue of ''[[The Atlantic]]'', in which he gave his perspective on the events just prior to the attack.<ref name=\"atlantic\">Miles, Sherman: \"[https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1969/12/pearl-harbor-in-retrospect/5485/ Pearl Harbor in Retrospect]\", ''The Atlantic'', July 1948. URL retrieved 2011-01-13.</ref>\n\nAfter the death of his wife Yulee in 1953, he married Edith Lawrence Coolidge, widow of [[Harold Jefferson Coolidge, Sr.]], in 1954.<ref name=\"beer\"/>\n\nHe died at the hospital in [[Beverly, Massachusetts]] after long illness<ref name=\"obit\"/> and was buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]] in the [[Miles Mausoleum]] on October 12, 1966.<ref name=\"arlington\"/>\n\n==Memberships==\nGeneral Miles joined the [[Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States]] as a Second Class Companion and, upon his father's death, became a Companion of the First Class.\n\n==Military awards==\n\nArmy General Staff Identification Badge\n{|\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Army of Cuban Pacification ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army of Cuban Pacification Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Mexican Border Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Mexican Border Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=World War I Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[World War I Victory Medal (United States)|World War I Victory Medal]] with three battle clasps\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Army of Occupation of Germany ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army of Occupation of Germany Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=American Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[American Defense Service Medal]] with Foreign Service Clasp\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=American Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[American Campaign Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=World War II Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[World War II Victory Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Legion Honneur Chevalier ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Legion of Honor|Chevalier of the Legion of Honor]]\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Henry L. Shattuck]]\t\n| title=Member of the [[Massachusetts House of Representatives]] from the 5th Suffolk District\n| years=1947 \u2013 1953\n| after=[[John Yerxa]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miles, Sherman}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Republicans]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sherman_Miles"}
{"title_page": "North and South (miniseries)", "text_new": "{{About|the American miniseries|the originating novels|North and South (trilogy)|the unrelated British television serial|North & South (TV serial)|other uses|North and South (disambiguation){{!}}North and South}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = North and South\n| image                = North+South-Complete1-3.jpg\n| image_size           = 250px\n| image_alt            =\n| caption              = Complete Collection [[DVD]] cover\n| genre                = [[Historical fiction]]\n| creator              = [[David L. Wolper]]\n| based_on             = {{Based on|''[[North and South (trilogy)|North and South]]'' (trilogy)|[[John Jakes]]}}\n| screenplay           =\n| story                = John Jakes\n| director             =\n| starring             = {{Plainlist|\n* [[James Read]]\n* [[Patrick Swayze]]\n* [[Lesley-Anne Down]]\n* [[Wendy Kilbourne]]\n* [[Kirstie Alley]]\n* [[Jean Simmons]]\n* [[Mitchell Ryan]]\n* [[Terri Garber]]\n* [[Genie Francis]]\n* [[Kyle Chandler]]\n* [[David Ogden Stiers]]\n* [[David Carradine]]\n* [[Jonathan Frakes]]\n* [[Hal Holbrook]]\n}}\n| narrated             =\n| theme_music_composer = [[Bill Conti]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = {{Plainlist|\n* ''Book I'': 6\n* ''Book II'': 6\n* ''Book III'': 3\n}}\n| producer             = Paul Freeman\n| editor               =\n| cinematography       = Stevan Larner, ASC\n| runtime              = 90 minutes/episode<br />1,342 mins. total\n| company              = [[David L. Wolper|David L. Wolper Productions]]<br />[[Warner Bros. Television]]\n| distributor          =\n| budget               =\n| network              = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| first_aired          = {{Plainlist|\n* ''Book I'': November 3, 1985\n* ''Book II'': May 4, 1986\n* ''Book III'': February 27, 1994\n}}\n| last_aired           =\n| preceded_by          =\n| followed_by          =\n| website              =\n|audio_format = ''Book I'' & ''Book II'': [[Monaural|Mono]]<br />''Book III'': [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n|picture_format= [[480i]] ([[NTSC]])\n}}\n'''''North and South''''' is the title of three American television [[miniseries]] broadcast on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] network in 1985, 1986, and 1994. Set before, during, and immediately after the [[American Civil War]], they are based on the 1980s [[trilogy]] of novels ''[[North and South (trilogy)|North and South]]'' by [[John Jakes]].<ref name=\"GB Review 1\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WHohAQAAIAAJ&dq=ISBN0151669988&ei=PsFCS_KYH5zElASGtYiuAQ&cd=1|title=Editorial Review: ''North and South'' (1982)|year=1982|work=[[Kirkus Reviews]]|accessdate=January 5, 2010}}</ref> The 1985 first installment, ''North and South'', remains the seventh-highest rated miniseries in TV history.<ref name=\"TS 2007-08\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribstar.com/news/lifestyles/john-jakes-journey-to-new-york-times-bestseller-list-included/article_8a3877e1-8e78-593d-9de8-b878d396254a.html|title=John Jakes' journey to ''New York Times'' bestseller list included boyhood years in Terre Haute|last=Bennett|first=Mark|date=August 11, 2007|work=[[Tribune-Star]]|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"P&C 2002\">{{cite web|url=http://www.depauw.edu/news/index.asp?id=11968|title=Bestselling novelist penning saga of fictional Charleston family|last=Thompson|first=Bill|date=March 18, 2002|work=[[The Post and Courier]]|publisher=Excerpted at DePauw.edu|accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"JJCC\">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Mary Ellen|title=John Jakes: A Critical Companion|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group|Greenwood Press]]|date=November 30, 1996|page=3|chapter=The People's Author: The Life of John Jakes|isbn=0-313-29530-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2pzmvCXfuoAC&pg=PA3&lpg=PA3&dq=highest+rated+miniseries+jakes&source=bl&ots=wMhwmYz79n&sig=gnjdl2g_URPhmDLhAGaKOBqpgvI&hl=en&ei=1VlFS9SuFZKuNtCCle0C&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CAcQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=&f=false|accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref> ''North and South: Book II'' (1986) was met with similar success, while 1994's ''Heaven  and Hell: North and South Book III'' was poorly received by both critics and audiences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewgraveyard.com/2008_reviews/dvd/08-10-20_north-south3.htm|title=North and South: Book III - Heaven and Hell - DVD review|work=reviewgraveyard.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/northandsouth.php|title=DVD Verdict Review - North And South: The Complete Collection|work=DVD Verdict}}</ref>\n\nThe saga tells the story of the enduring friendship between Orry Main of [[South Carolina]] ([[Patrick Swayze]]) and George Hazard of [[Pennsylvania]] ([[James Read]]), who become best friends while attending the [[United States Military Academy|United States Military Academy at West Point]] but later find themselves and their families on opposite sides of the war.<ref name=\"GB Review 1\"/> The slave-owning Mains are rural planters from outside Charleston, South Carolina, while the Hazards, who resided in a small Pennsylvania mill town, profit from ownership of iron manufacturing and industry capital, their differences reflecting the divisions between North and South that eventually led to the Civil War.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/01/arts/tv-weekend-north-and-south-a-mini-series.html|title=TV Weekend; ''North and South'', A Mini-series|last=O'Connor|first=John J.|date=November 1, 1985|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=NYTimes.com|accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\nThe initial 1985 miniseries cast [[Patrick Swayze]] as Orry Main and [[James Read]] as George Hazard with [[Lesley-Anne Down]] as Orry's love interest Madeline and [[Wendy Kilbourne]] as George's future wife Constance.<ref name=\"NYM 1985\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7McBAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA58&dq=Slavs,+Slaves,+Shoulders&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAGoVChMI-fn2qubxxgIVDhKSCh2DkA6u#v=onepage&q=Slavs%2C%20Slaves%2C%20Shoulders&f=false|title=Slavs, Slaves, and Shoulders (Review: ''North and South'')|last=Leonard|first=John|date=November 4, 1985|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|pages=58\u201361|accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref> [[Kirstie Alley]] played George's outspoken [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]] sister Virgilia, with [[Genie Francis]] as Orry's \"good\" sister Brett and [[Terri Garber]] as his selfish and wicked sister Ashton, as well as [[Philip Casnoff]] as Elkanah Bent, George and Orry's nemesis.<ref name=\"NYM 1985\"/> All of these actors returned for the 1986 [[sequel]], joined by [[Parker Stevenson]] as Billy Hazard, George's brother and Brett's husband.<ref name=\"NYM 1986\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DucCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA85&dq=The+Blue,+The+Gray,+and+the+D%C3%A9shabille&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDgQ6AEwA2oVChMIodWX1ebxxgIVlICSCh2boghz#v=onepage&q=The%20Blue%2C%20The%20Gray%2C%20and%20the%20D%C3%A9shabille&f=false |title=The Blue, The Gray, and the D\u00e9shabille (Review: ''North and South: Book II'')|last=Leonard|first=John|date=May 5, 1986|work=New York|page=85|accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\n''North and South'' (1985) also featured many well-known actors as guest stars, including [[Elizabeth Taylor]] as bordello proprietor Madam Conti, [[David Carradine]] as the sadistic Justin LaMotte, [[Hal Holbrook]] as [[Abraham Lincoln]], [[Gene Kelly]] as Bent's father Senator Charles Edwards, [[Robert Mitchum]] as Colonel Patrick Flynn, M.D., [[Johnny Cash]] as abolitionist [[John Brown (abolitionist)|John Brown]], [[Jean Simmons]] as Orry's mother Clarissa Main, [[Mitchell Ryan]] as Orry's father Tillet Main, [[John Anderson (actor)|John Anderson]] as George's father William Hazard,  [[Jonathan Frakes]] as George's older brother Stanley Hazard,  [[Inga Swenson]] as George's mother Maude Hazard, [[Robert Guillaume]] as abolitionist  [[Frederick Douglass]], [[Morgan Fairchild]] as Burdetta Halloran, [[David Ogden Stiers]] as Congressman Sam Greene, and [[Olivia Cole]] as Madeline's devoted but doomed servant Maum Sally.<ref name=\"NYM 1985\"/> John Jakes' wife Rachel also made an appearance in Episode 6 as Lincoln's wife [[Mary Todd Lincoln|Mary]].  ''North and South: Book II'' (1986) saw the return of Carradine as LaMotte, Holbrook as Lincoln, and Stiers as Congressman Greene, as well as new guests [[Lloyd Bridges]] as [[Jefferson Davis]], [[Anthony Zerbe]] as [[Ulysses S. Grant]], [[Nancy Marchand]] as [[Dorothea Dix]], [[James Stewart]] as Miles Colbert, [[Wayne Newton]] as Captain Thomas Turner, and [[William Schallert]] as [[Robert E. Lee]],<ref name=\"NYM 1986\"/> with [[Linda Evans]] as Rose Sinclair and [[Olivia de Havilland]] as Mrs. Neal.  1994's ''Heaven and Hell'' featured [[Peter O'Toole]] as \"louche actor\" Sam Trump<ref name=\"Variety 1994\">{{cite book|url=https://variety.com/1994/tv/reviews/john-jakes-heaven-and-hell-north-and-south-part-3-1200435663/|title=Review: John Jakes' ''Heaven and Hell: North and South Part 3''|last=O'Connell|first=Patricia|date=February 25, 1994|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=January 7, 2010}}</ref> and [[Billy Dee Williams]] as [[Francis Cardozo]].\n\nFilming of the miniseries resulted in four marriages among the cast and crew. Read and Kilbourne, who played opposite each other, married in 1988 and now have two children. Frakes and Francis, who had previously played opposite each other on the failed NBC soap ''[[Bare Essence]]'', also married in 1988. Lesley-Anne Down married assistant cameraman Don E. FauntLeRoy in 1986. They met during filming of ''Book I'' when both were married to other people, and eventually obtained divorces.<ref>{{cite web|last=Allis|first=Tim|title=The Spoils of War|work=[[People (magazine)|People magazine]]|date=February 28, 1994|publisher=Vol. 41, No. 8 |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20107588,00.html|accessdate=January 16, 2010}}</ref> Garber married screenwriter Chris Hager, whom she met in 1985 when he worked as a grip on the set of ''North and South: Book II''. They had a daughter, Molly, in 1986, and later divorced.<ref name=\"TVG 1987\">{{cite journal |journal=[[TV Guide]] |title=The Fall and Rise of Terri Garber |date=September 5, 1987 |issue=1797}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!! style=\"background:#daa520;\"|Character\n!! style=\"background:#daa520;\"|''North and South''<br />1985\n!! style=\"background:#daa520;\"|''North and South: Book II''<br />1986\n!! style=\"background:#daa520;\"|''Heaven and Hell:<br />North and South Book III''<br />1994\n|-\n| Orry Main                        || colspan=\"2\"| [[Patrick Swayze]]                || Patrick Swayze (archive/uncredited)\n|-\n| George Hazard                    || colspan=\"3\"| [[James Read]]  \n|-\n| Madeline Fabray                  || colspan=\"3\"|[[Lesley-Anne Down]]    \n|-\n| Constance Flynn                  || colspan=\"3\"|[[Wendy Kilbourne]]      \n|-\n| Virgilia Hazard                  || colspan=\"2 \"|[[Kirstie Alley]]                            || \u2013\n|-\n| Ashton Main                     {{indent|3}}Young Ashton {{indent|3}}Young Ashton       || [[Terri Garber]]<br />[[Temi Epstein]] (Ep. 1)<br />Stephanie Jolluck (Ep. 2)           || Terri Garber|| Terri Garber\n|-\n| Brett Main                     {{indent|3}}Young Brett {{indent|3}}Young Brett         || [[Genie Francis]]<br />Nikki Creswell (Ep. 1)<br />Melissa Manley (Ep. 2)            || Genie Francis|| Genie Francis\n|-\n| Elkanah Bent                     || colspan=\"3\"|[[Philip Casnoff]]     \n|-\n| Charles Main                     || colspan=\"2\"| [[Lewis Smith (actor)|Lewis Smith]]                    || [[Kyle Chandler]]\n|-\n| Billy Hazard  {{indent|3}}Young Billy    || [[John Samuels|John Stockwell]]<br />[[Cary Guffey]] (Ep. 1)   || [